    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-10T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-10T22:00:00-05:00" n="349"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d349">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115/56: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-11T12:00:00+09:00"
                            >September 11, 1937—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received September 11—5:05
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>361. Department’s 194, September 8, 7 p.m.,<note n="20" xml:id="d349fn20">Not
                        printed; it repeated Shanghai’s No. 667, September 7, 8 p.m., <ref
                            target="#pg_313">p. 313</ref>, and instructed the Ambassador that after
                        consultation with his interested colleagues he might, in his discretion,
                        make an informal approach to the Japanese Government (393.115/55).</note>
                    access by businessmen to Northern District Shanghai.</p>
                <pb facs="0328" n="320" xml:id="pg_320"/>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>A member of my staff took up the matter with Yoshizawa<note n="21"
                            xml:id="d349fn21">Seijiro Yoshizawa, Director of the American Affairs
                            Bureau, Japanese Foreign Office.</note> at the Foreign Office yesterday
                        morning, leaving an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>My British colleague proposes to act along the same lines. My French
                        colleague will act if he hears from his colleague at Nanking. My German
                        colleague has already made an oral approach on the basis of instructions
                        from Berlin previous to the receipt of my letter to him. My Italian
                        colleague made an oral approach yesterday.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai for relay to Nanking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
